column2: The epiblast is well-established to emerge from the ICM. See PMID 24968703
column3: The hypoblast is well-established to emerge from the ICM. See PMID 24968703
column5: The parietal endoderm is well-established to arise from the hypoblast. See PMID 24968703
column6: The visceral endoderm is well-established to arise from the hypoblast. See PMID 24968703
column10: The embryonic visceral endoderm (EmVE) is well-established to arise from the visceral endoderm. See PMID 24968703
column11: The extraembryonic visceral endoderm (ExVE) is well-established to arise from the visceral endoderm. See PMID 24968703
column19: The primitive streak is well-established to arise from the epiblast. See PMID 24968703
column27: The nascent mesoderm is well-established to arise from the epiblast. See PMID 22170865
column31: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.24) that is likely explained by the continuous relationship between the ectoderm around the primitive streak and the remainder of the epiblast.
column34: Hematoendothelial progenitors are well-established to arise from nascent mesoderm. See PMID 28859300
column35: The cell state that we annotate as mixed mesoderm, the annotation applied to it by Pijuan-Sala et al. (2019) (PMID 30787436), is inferred to arise from nascent mesoderm.
column37: The anterior primitive streak is well-established to arise from the primitive streak. See PMID 10611967
column38: Primordial germ cells (PGCs) are well-established to arise at the posterior primitive streak. See PMID 23125014.
column39: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.24) that is likely explained by the continuous relationship between the ectoderm around the primitive streak and the remainder of the epiblast.
column41: The definitive endoderm is well-established to arise from the anterior primitive streak. See PMID 10611967
column42: The notochord is well-established to arise from the anterior primitive streak. See PMID 26845388
column47: Blood progenitors, presumably primitive at this stage, are well established to arise from hematoendothelial progenitors. Nomenclature from original study (PMID 30787436)
column49: Amniochorionic mesoderm (tentative label; these cells called mesenchyme by PMID 30787436) appears to arise from mixed mesoderm.
column50: Self, with an additional edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.24) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column51: Self, with an additional edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.24) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column56: Self, with an additional edge back to mixed mesoderm (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column58: Self, with an additional edge back to anterior primitive streak (weight 0.30) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column59: Gut is well-established to arise from definitive endoderm. See PMID 10611967
column60: Self, with an additional edge back to hematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.28) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column61: Self, with an additional edge back to anterior primitive streak (weight 0.30) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column62: Gut is well-established to arise from definitive endoderm. See PMID 10611967
column65: Rostral neuroectoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to epiblast (0.53) and primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm (0.47). See PMID 29109536.
column68: Self, with an additional edge back to hematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.28) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column70: Self, with an additional edge back to mixed mesoderm (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or a continuum
column71: Extraembryonic mesoderm appears to arise from mixed mesoderm. Note that although this cell state is related to allantois at next timepoint, in general, distinction from other mesodermal cell populations is challenging. See PMID 22855605.
column72: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.68) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column73: Splanchnic mesoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to both nascent (0.61) and mixed (0.39) mesoderm. See PMID 16304598.
column74: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.68) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
column76: Paraxial mesoderm A appears to arise from the nascent mesoderm. Distinguished from other paraxial mesoderm cell states based on markers Tbx1, Pax3, and potentially corresponds to anterior paraxial mesoderm. See PMID 23081715, PMID 20692252. Paraxial mesoderm ABC appears to correspond to rostral > caudal gradient.
column77: Paraxial mesoderm B appears to arise from the nascent mesoderm. Distinguished from other paraxial mesoderm cell states based on markers Tbx6, Dll1, and potentially corresponds to posterior paraxial mesoderm. See PMID 15986483, PMID 20692252. Paraxial mesoderm ABC appears to correspond to rostral > caudal gradient
column78: Splanchnic mesoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to both nascent (0.61) and mixed (0.39) mesoderm. See PMID 16304598.
column81: Caudal lateral epiblast appears to arise from primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm, marked by Nkx1-2 aka Sax1. See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/045872v1.
column82: Caudal neuroectoderm appears to arise from primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm. See PMID 11748135.
column84: Rostral neuroectoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to epiblast (0.53) and primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm (0.47). See PMID 29109536.
column85: Surface ectoderm appears to emerge from primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm. May reflect that primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm comprises a substantial region, as caudal neuroectoderm and caudal lateral epiblast also have edges back to primitive streak and adjacent ectoderm, while epiblast associated with rostral neuroectoderm. See PMID 26690418.
column89: Primitive erythroid cells are well-established to emerge from blood progenitors. See PMID 24478716.
column91: Paraxial mesoderm C emerges with edges back to both nascent mesoderm (0.69) and caudal lateral epiblast (0.27). See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/045872v1. Paraxial mesoderm ABC appears to correspond to rostral > caudal gradient
